<review_text>

it is difficult , nay , impossible , to like a book when all the characters are obnoxious , money worshipping parasites , and that is exactly what we have in this novel .
out of the blue a godfather appears , a deus ex machina , who offers an idealistic lawyer , clay carter , more wealth than he can imagine or use .
anyone with a brain would know that there has to be a hook within the bait , a very sharp , very large hook .
with apparent ease , this naive lawyer swallows the hook and makes millions and millions of dollars before he so much as senses that he is in deep trouble .
enthralled with the gaudy toys and women that money brings him , he immediately loses sight of reality .
what a hollow and useless individual he is , as are those he hires to assist him and those with whom he associates in his lawyer world .
whether or not there are such individuals ( enron ?
) is beside the point .
they may exist , but i for one am not eager to hear their life stories .
the atmosphere in which they live is boring , as are their conversations , their lack of values , their hobbies , their sex lives , and their comeuppances .
somehow , even in their fall , they never lose all their money and they never quite realize what hollow individuals they are .
