<review_text>

this play explores the same old turf as " death of a salesman " , but it does so with much less satisfaction and much less character development .
eddie is no willy loman , though , and the play suffers immediately from a lack of a central , driving force like willy .
parts of the play seem borrowed from tennessee williams , and they do n't seem to work in this context .
there is some business about the romance of the old world italy versus the new world of opportunity on the docks of new york , and it is the only topic that is at all explored well , if still unsatisfactorily .
eddie 's dreams are represented in his pretty niece , catherine ; and unlike willy loman 's uncle , she is still an attainable dream .
that makes eddie 's life seem all the more petty , in comparison to willy 's : he longs wearily not after what he could have had , but after what he can never have , as he is already married .
the death scene at the end of the play also seems like a forced , tacked on ending , and alfieri 's entire presence is a more or less unsuccessful stage gimmick .
there are better plays by miller , and many better plays by others

